=== Beispiel-Pipelines ===

## 1. Einfach — HTTP-Fetch + Verarbeitung

  brix__create_pipeline(
    name="fetch-and-process",
    description="Daten von API holen und verarbeiten",
    params=[
      {"name": "url", "type": "string", "required": True},
      {"name": "output_path", "type": "string", "default": "/host/root/output.json"}
    ],
    steps=[
      {
        "id": "fetch",
        "type": "http",
        "config": {"url": "{{ input.url }}", "method": "GET"}
      },
      {
        "id": "process",
        "type": "python",
        "config": {
          "code": """
import json
data = input_data.get('items', [])
result = [{'id': x['id'], 'name': x['name']} for x in data]
"""
        },
        "input": "{{ fetch.output }}"
      },
      {
        "id": "save",
        "type": "python",
        "config": {
          "code": "import json; open(output_path, 'w').write(json.dumps(result, indent=2))"
        },
        "input": {
          "result": "{{ process.output }}",
          "output_path": "{{ input.output_path }}"
        }
      }
    ]
  )

## 2. Mittel — foreach mit Parallelverarbeitung

  brix__create_pipeline(
    name="batch-pdf-extract",
    description="PDFs parallel verarbeiten",
    params=[{"name": "pdf_dir", "type": "string", "required": True}],
    steps=[
      {
        "id": "list_files",
        "type": "python",
        "config": {
          "code": """
import os, glob
result = [{"path": p, "name": os.path.basename(p)}
          for p in glob.glob(os.path.join(pdf_dir, '*.pdf'))]
"""
        },
        "input": {"pdf_dir": "{{ input.pdf_dir }}"}
      },
      {
        "id": "extract",
        "type": "python",
        "foreach": "{{ list_files.output }}",
        "concurrency": 4,
        "config": {
          "code": """
# item.path ist der Pfad zur PDF
result = {"path": item["path"], "text": extract_pdf(item["path"])}
"""
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "summary",
        "type": "python",
        "config": {
          "code": """
results = [r["output"] for r in items if r["success"]]
result = {"count": len(results), "extracted": results}
"""
        },
        "input": {"items": "{{ extract.results }}"}
      }
    ]
  )

## 3. Komplex — Multi-Stage mit Credentials + Conditionals

  brix__create_pipeline(
    name="email-report-pipeline",
    description="Mails holen, klassifizieren, Report senden",
    params=[
      {"name": "folder", "type": "string", "default": "Inbox"},
      {"name": "send_report", "type": "boolean", "default": True}
    ],
    steps=[
      {
        "id": "fetch_mails",
        "type": "mcp",
        "config": {
          "server": "m365",
          "tool": "list-mail-messages",
          "params": {"folder": "{{ input.folder }}", "top": 50}
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "classify",
        "type": "python",
        "foreach": "{{ fetch_mails.output.value }}",
        "concurrency": 5,
        "config": {
          "helper": "mail_classifier",
          "params": {"subject": "{{ item.subject }}", "body": "{{ item.bodyPreview }}"}
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "build_report",
        "type": "python",
        "config": {
          "code": """
classified = [r["output"] for r in items if r["success"]]
categories = {}
for c in classified:
    cat = c.get("category", "other")
    categories[cat] = categories.get(cat, 0) + 1
result = {"total": len(classified), "categories": categories}
"""
        },
        "input": {"items": "{{ classify.results }}"}
      },
      {
        "id": "send_report",
        "type": "mcp",
        "when": "{{ input.send_report }}",
        "config": {
          "server": "m365",
          "tool": "send-mail",
          "params": {
            "to": "user@example.com",
            "subject": "Mail-Report",
            "body": "{{ build_report.output | tojson }}"
          }
        }
      }
    ]
  )

=== DAG-Mode — Parallele Steps mit depends_on ===

## Konzept

Standardmäßig werden Steps sequentiell ausgeführt.
Mit depends_on können Steps Abhängigkeiten deklarieren → parallele Ausführung wo möglich.

## Syntax

  {
    "id": "step_a",
    "type": "python",
    "config": {"code": "result = fetch_data_a()"}
  },
  {
    "id": "step_b",
    "type": "python",
    "config": {"code": "result = fetch_data_b()"}
  },
  {
    "id": "merge",
    "type": "python",
    "depends_on": ["step_a", "step_b"],   ← Wartet auf beide
    "config": {
      "code": "result = combine(step_a_out, step_b_out)"
    },
    "input": {
      "step_a_out": "{{ step_a.output }}",
      "step_b_out": "{{ step_b.output }}"
    }
  }

  → step_a und step_b laufen PARALLEL
  → merge startet erst wenn BEIDE fertig sind

## Fan-out / Fan-in Pattern

  fetch_a ──┐
  fetch_b ──┼── merge ── output
  fetch_c ──┘

  Ideal für:
  • Parallele API-Calls
  • Unabhängige Daten-Fetches
  • Parallele LLM-Aufrufe

## Zyklen

  Zyklen in depends_on werden zur Validierungszeit erkannt:
  brix__validate_pipeline(name="my-dag") gibt CYCLE_DETECTED zurück

=== Helper-Scripts ===

## Was sind Helpers?

Helper sind Python-Skripte die in Pipeline-Steps eingebunden werden können.
Sie ermöglichen komplexe Logik die über einfache python-Bricks hinausgeht.

## Helper erstellen

  brix__create_helper(
    name="my_processor",
    description="Verarbeitet Eingabe-Daten",
    code="""
#!/usr/bin/env python3
import json, sys

def main():
    if len(sys.argv) > 1:
        params = json.loads(sys.argv[1])
    elif not sys.stdin.isatty():
        raw = sys.stdin.read().strip()
        params = json.loads(raw) if raw else {}
    else:
        params = {}

    result = {"processed": params.get("value", "") + "_done"}
    print(json.dumps(result))

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
"""
  )

## Helper registrieren (für Pipeline-Nutzung)

  brix__register_helper(name="my_processor")

## Helper in Pipeline nutzen

  {
    "id": "process",
    "type": "python",
    "config": {
      "helper": "my_processor",
      "params": {"value": "{{ input.data }}"}
    }
  }

## Brix SDK (in Helpers verfügbar)

  import brix.sdk as sdk

  sdk.mcp.call(server, tool, params)   # MCP-Tool aufrufen
  sdk.progress(step, total, message)   # Fortschritt reporten
  sdk.is_cancelled()                   # Abbruch prüfen

  Beispiel:
  if sdk.is_cancelled():
      sys.exit(0)

  sdk.progress(current=5, total=10, message="Verarbeite Batch...")

  result = sdk.mcp.call(
      server="m365",
      tool="list-mail-messages",
      params={"folder": "Inbox"}
  )

